  • funseq score = 0-6 (6 = most "deleterious")
  • 0-base vs 1-base:
    • 1-based = GFF, SAM, VCF
      • SNP = chr1:5-5 T/A
      • INS = chr1:3-4 -/TTA
      • DEL = chr1:5-5 T/-
    • 0-based = BED, BAM
      • SNP = chr1:4-5 T/A
      • INS = chr1:3-3 -/TTA
      • DEL = chr1:4-5 T/-
        • places in Funseq/CNCDriver code w/ 0/1-based matters:
        • Variant input should be 0 based, end exclusive (ie chr1:0-100 = spans basepairs 0-99)
        • utils-extractElementMutations.R line ~57 (dat$posStart<-dat$posStart+1, to correct 0-index start position)

## Filtering samples for those that are TNBC only
TNBC_TCGApeaks = TCGApeaks.loc[:,TCGApeaks.columns.isin(TNBClist)]
TNBC_peak2gene = peak2gene.loc[:,peak2gene.columns.isin(TNBClist)]

## Adding column that counts number of samples that the peak (or peak-gene link) is present in
TNBC_TCGApeaks['count'] = TNBC_TCGApeaks.sum(axis = 'columns')
TNBC_peak2gene['count'] = TNBC_peak2gene.sum(axis = 'columns')

## Dropping peaks that aren't open in any samples
TNBC_TCGApeaks = TNBC_TCGApeaks.loc[TNBC_TCGApeaks['count'] != 0] # 562,709 -> 481,938 unique peaks
TNBC_peak2gene = TNBC_peak2gene.loc[TNBC_peak2gene['count'] != 0] #61,502 -> 44,992 unique peak-gene links

## for peak2gene table, some peak2gene links have the same peak (ie peak1-gene1, peak1-gene2) -> for each peak, calculate # of samples w/ that peak linked to at least 1 gene; ie Pt A has p1-g1 link and Pt B has p1-g2 link; that means that p1 has a link in 2 samples

## 1) Split up peak-gene link into peak, gene
TNBC_peak2gene['gene'], TNBC_peak2gene['peak'] = TNBC_peak2gene.index.str.rsplit('-',1).str
# print(len(TNBC_peak2gene['peak'].unique())) #35866 unique peaks that have links

## 2) make an empty df to add counts to
TNBC_p2g_peakCount = pd.DataFrame(index = TNBC_peak2gene['peak'].unique(), columns = ['count'])

## 3) Add in the counts for peaks with only 1 gene link
### 3a) drop all duplicates
temp_df_1peakTo1gene = TNBC_peak2gene.drop_duplicates(subset = 'peak', keep = False)
### 3b) make list of peaks that only are linked to 1 gene
temp_list_1peakTo1gene = temp_df_1peakTo1gene['peak'].to_list()
# print(len(temp_list_1peakTo1gene))
### 3c) for each peak (with only 1 gene), add the count to the new TNBC_p2g_peakCount
for i in temp_list_1peakTo1gene:
    TNBC_p2g_peakCount.loc[i,'count'] = TNBC_peak2gene.loc[(TNBC_peak2gene['peak'] == i),'count'].values[0]
## did sanity check where I took all the peaks that still had NaN (ie weren't filled in b/c theoretically they had more than 1 gene that they regulated) and overlapped it with a list of known duplicatePeaks, it checked out :) 100% overlap, there are 6735 peaks with links to more than 1 gene

## 2) Deal w/ the peaks w/ links to >1 gene (ie peak1-gene1, peak1-gene2)
TNBC_p2g_duplicatePeaks = TNBC_peak2gene[TNBC_peak2gene.duplicated(subset = 'peak', keep = False)]
duplicatePeakList = list(TNBC_p2g_duplicatePeaks['peak'].unique())
print(len(duplicatePeakList))
for i in duplicatePeakList:
    temp_df = TNBC_p2g_duplicatePeaks[TNBC_p2g_duplicatePeaks['peak'] == i]
    # add a row called "p2gLinksInPatient" that counts the #links in patient
    temp_df.loc['#p2gLinksInPatient'] = temp_df.sum(axis = 'index')
    noPeakCount = (temp_df.loc['#p2gLinksInPatient'] == 0).sum()
    peakCount = 15 - noPeakCount
    TNBC_p2g_peakCount.loc[i,'count'] = peakCount
#did sanity check, there are no NaN values :) and no values over 15 (which is the max number of samples)

0.1.3 Making Venn diagram: MDA231 vs TNBCs Peaks AND how many new peaks does each sample add?¶

Making a venn diagram of peaks open in MDA231 vs TNBC. Also doing the same for peaks w/ link

Open peaks 1.1) Find open peaks in MDA231 (done on cluster b/c file is big) 1.2) make a list of open peaks in MDA231 & make a list of open peaks in TNBCs 1.3) Make venn diagram

Peaks w/ link 2.1) filter out rows where MDA-MB-231 has a value of 0 (ie no link) 2.2) format table p2gCellLines to have a column for peaks and another for genes (ie rsplit) 2.3) make a list of unique peaks that have a link predicted for MDA-MB-231 2.4) Do the same for the TNBC dataframe 2.5) Overlap the lists and make venn diagram

0 - Funseq and CNCDriver on 31 PCAWG samples¶

OVERALL:

  • started with 1.5mil PCAWG variants -> 253,640 TNBC variants (including in promoter, enhancer, etc regions) in 253,584 unique locations (ie at location chr1 104 105 you could have C->T or C->G, so 2 different variants, but 1 location)

    • per sample analysis: min (i.e. sample w/ least amount of variants) = 2107 variants, max = 18,802 variants, mean = 8,182 variants/sample, mode = ~2000-4000 variants/sample

  • Ran through the following contexts: BRCA, TNBC (coding vs -nc tag); and intereactive vs bash. Some analysis is shown in 0.3.4.4 however in general there was no/minor differences btwn all of the various settings

    • TNBC vs BRCA Context = same # of variants (250,724), but some difference in output (likely d/t HUB annotations, ie (RYBP:BRCA_REG(0.135)PHOS(0.276)TNBC_REG(0.140)) though didn't do analysis to check this... (could possibly look at variantSampleID overlap btwn the two in the future)

  • Since all overlap was similar, I used: TNBC context, no -nc tag, Bash script. Results were:

    • 250,746 variants (so ~3k variants not included; WHY??????)

0.2 - Finding TCGA/PCAWG TNBC data¶

## 1a) https://rpubs.com/tiagochst/BCR_Biotab
## In Terminal
## conda install -c conda-forge r-purrrogress

############ In R ######################
###### Downloading stuff ######

# if (!require("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
#   install.packages("BiocManager")
## Had to do below b/c one of TCGAbiolinks dependencies (purrrogress) was taken down from CRAN
# remotes::install_github("RDocTaskForce/parsetools")
# remotes::install_github("RDocTaskForce/testextra")
# BiocManager::install("halpo/purrrogress")
# BiocManager::install("TCGAbiolinks")

###### Actual code :) ######
library(TCGAbiolinks)

## Writing the query
query <- GDCquery(project = "TCGA-BRCA",
                  data.category = "Clinical",
                  data.type = "Clinical Supplement",
                  data.format = "BCR Biotab")
## Downloading the query from GDC
GDCdownload(query)
## "GDCprepare" reads the data and makes it into an R object, it gets assigned to a list of tibbles (tibbles = bascially dataframes; so it is a list of dataframes) that has all of the GDC data we just downloaded
clinical.BCRtab.all <- GDCprepare(query)
## this is just printing the name of all 9 of the dataframes
names(clinical.BCRtab.all)
## we want the dataframe/tibble called "clinical_patient_brca" which has the IHC info... note, just gonna save it to a dataframe so that I can work w/ it in python :P
table = clinical.BCRtab.all$clinical_patient_brca
typeof(table) # "list"
write.table(table,file="~/Documents/khuranalab/P5_AOCproject/P5_0.2_clinical_patient_brca.csv")

###### looking at the dataframe :) ######
TCGA_clinicalBrca = pd.read_csv('/Users/annpalladino/Documents/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/P5_0.2_clinical_patient_brca.csv', sep = ',') # note, the most recently dx'd patient was in 2013; so i feel like there's more up to date ones

0.3 Run Funseq & CNCDriver on PCAWG data¶

0.3.1 - Getting sample list¶

NOTES: I used the TNBC samples from 0.2 block (https://rpubs.com/tiagochst/BCR_Biotab) and overlapped them with the PCAWG samples. All samples used are from BRCA-US project

For the 31 samples cohort (didn't use these 3 b/c of overlap w/ nikZainal, make sure all PCAWG analysis is on 28 samples): I then added 3 extra samples (PD4086, PD4109, PD4248) that were TNBCs according to the paper below (is a Nik-Zainal paper). These samples had 2 DO### numbers on ICGC, one corresponded to the ER+/HER- EU/UK project and one corresponded to the TNBC/lobular BRCA-UK project. I used the one listed in the BRCA-UK project. Authors don't say how they defined TNBCs. Nik-Zainal paper (2012; TNBCs labeled in Fig 4 as well as others): https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/1-s2.0-S0092867412005272-mmc2.pdf

In [5]:
path = '/Users/annpalladino/Documents/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/'
## Get TCGA IHC data
TCGA_clinicalBrca = pd.read_csv(path + 'P5_AOCproject/P5_0.2_clinical_patient_brca.csv', sep = ',') # note, the most recently dx'd patient was in 2013; so i feel like there's more up to date ones
TCGA_clinicalBrca_TNBC = TCGA_clinicalBrca[(TCGA_clinicalBrca['er_status_by_ihc'] == 'Negative') & (TCGA_clinicalBrca['pr_status_by_ihc'] == 'Negative') & (TCGA_clinicalBrca['her2_status_by_ihc'] == 'Negative')]

TCGA_clinicalBrca_TNBC_list = TCGA_clinicalBrca_TNBC['bcr_patient_barcode'].to_list() # This column has the "TCGA-A1-A0SK" labels

## 1) filter by TNBCs
import pandas as pd
PCAWG_variants_hg19 = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/1_FunseqInput/PCAWG/TNBC/raw_alm_Breast-Cancer_PCAWG_SNV_hg19.beb', sep ='\t', header = None)

tempdf = TNBC_metadata[['tumour_specimen_aliquot_id','submitted_donor_id','icgc_donor_id']] 
tempdf

0.3.4 - Running FunSeq2 on PCAWG samples + Analysis¶

0.3.4.1 - EXPLANATION FOR FUNSEQ2 INPUT and OUTPUT (text only)¶

INPUT (there are more in actual documentation)

  • -f = input file name;; -inf = input file format (BED vs VCF), -nc = noncoding, o = output path (if running in nawaf's forlder, specificy somewhere else for package to write the output files b/c otherwise it tries to write them into nawaf's directory);;
  • -maf = minor allele frequency threshold; set at 1 for
#¶

OUTPUT

  • gerp = gerp score (i.e. 5.69) = evolutionary conservation score; high score = highly conserved

  • cds = coding sequence (yes/no) = should all be no for enhancers

  • variant.annotation.cds = gerp;cds;variant.annotation.cds;network.hub;gene.under.negative.selection; ENCODE.annotated;hot.region;motif.analysis;sensitive;ultra.sensitive;ultra.conserved;target.gene[known_cancer_gene/ TF_regulating_known_cancer_gene,differential_expressed_in_cancer,actionable_gene];coding.score;noncoding.score; recurrence.within.samples;recurrence.database

0.3.4.2 - BASH CODE for running FunSeq on TNBC samples; Contexts = Nawaf, BRCA (andre), and TNBC (andre)¶

In [ ]:
####### ONLY DO THIS WHOLE BLOCK ONCE #######
## 1) copy NAWAF data context and code  over
cp -R /athena/khuranalab/scratch/naa4013/funseq_hg38_data_context/ /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001 # copy Nawaf data context over;; note, will get some errors b/c can't unzip .gz files but thats fine, it'll still copy the .gz files over which is all that's needed
cp -R /athena/khuranalab/scratch/naa4013/funseq2_recent /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/ # copy code over

########################################################

## 1a) copy BRCA data context files over
# sensitive regions
cp /home/anf2034/sensitive_BRCA_hg38.bed /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context
# regulatory network
cp /home/anf2034/BRCA.regulatory.network /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context 
# peak-gene networks
cp /home/anf2034/BRCA_sample_drm.gene_hg38.bed /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context 
# Network
cp /athena/khuranalab/scratch/anf2034/FunSeq2/data_context/networks/REG.degree /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context # reg.degree file; NOTE, don't move directly to networks file b/c will replace original REG.degree file. instead, copy to my directory, rename (see below) and then move to the networks directory; just need to do for this file b/c Andre named it REG.degree... the rest he named more specifically (ie tnbc_Reg.degree)
mv /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context/REG.degree /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context/BRCA_REG.degree # Rename file
mv BRCA_REG.degree networks/ # move to networks directory

##############################################################

## 1b) copy TNBC data context files over
# sensitive regions
cp /home/anf2034/sensitive_TNBC_hg38.bed /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context
# regulatory network
cp /home/anf2034/TNBC.regulatory.network /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context 
# peak-gene networks
cp /home/anf2034/TNBC_sample_drm.gene_hg38.bed /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg38_data_context

## add duxPredictedGenes column to dataframe; based off of p2gDic
FSoutput_vcf_formatted['duxPredictedGenes'] = FSoutput_vcf_formatted['enhancer'].map(p2gDic)
# d(FSoutput_vcf_formatted) # note, there are a bunch of NaN for duxPredictedGenes b/c not all the peaks had links to genes

## Yay :) worked; did in a tempdf so i didn't mess up original FSoutput_vcf_formatted...
tempdf = FSoutput_vcf_formatted[['variantSampleID','GENE']]
tempdf.set_index('variantSampleID', inplace = True)
tempdf = tempdf.dropna() #20,381 -> 13,231
tempdf['GENElist'] = tempdf['GENE'].str.split(',')
tempdf['FunseqGeneList'] = ''

for i in tempdf.index:
    tempList = tempdf.loc[i,'GENElist']
    tempList_formatted = [(re.sub(r"\([^()]*\)", "", x)) for x in tempList]
    tempdf.loc[i,'FunseqGeneList'] = tempList_formatted

# d(tempdf)
# now merge tempdf back w/ FSoutput_vcf_formatted
tempdf = tempdf[['FunseqGeneList']]
# d(tempdf)
FSoutput_vcf_formatted = pd.merge(FSoutput_vcf_formatted,tempdf, how='left', left_on='variantSampleID', right_index=True)
d(FSoutput_vcf_formatted)

## 1) See if tnbcTNBC w/wo CDS is different
## 1a) make list of columns for each df
temp_FSoutInteractive_col = FSoutput_interactive.columns
temp_FSoutCDS_col = FSoutput_CDS.columns
## 1b) make a column for each df that is filled w/ concatenation of all columns (ie kinda like variantSampleID column but ALL columns are joined together)
FSoutput_interactive['temp'] = FSoutput_interactive[temp_FSoutInteractive_col].apply(lambda row: '_'.join(row.values.astype(str)), axis = 1)
FSoutput_CDS['temp'] = FSoutput_CDS[temp_FSoutCDS_col].apply(lambda row: '_'.join(row.values.astype(str)), axis = 1)
## 1c) look for overlap between the two "temp" columns
list1 = list(FSoutput_interactive['temp'])
list2 = list(FSoutput_CDS['temp'])
## below is modified from "overlap" function
set1 = set(list1)
set2 = set(list2)
print('len list1: ',len(list1),'; unique: ',len(set1))
print('len list2: ',len(list2),'; unique: ',len(set2))
print('len list1 U list2 (no repeats!): ',len(set1.union(set2)))
print('len list1  list2 : ', len(set1 & set2))
## len list1:  250724 ; unique:  250724
## len list2:  250724 ; unique:  250724
## len list1 U list2 (no repeats!):  250724
## len list1  list2 :  250724

#### So NCDS and CDS are the SAME!!! :), at least for these samples; maybe b/c of the context I used #######

## Gene analysis
FSoutput_vcf_formatted['#genesOverlapping'] = ''
for i in FSoutput_vcf_formatted.index:
    if pd.isnull(FSoutput_vcf_formatted.loc[i,'duxPredictedGenes']) or pd.isnull(FSoutput_vcf_formatted.loc[i,'FunseqGeneList']):
        FSoutput_vcf_formatted.loc[i,'#genesOverlapping'] = np.NaN
    else:
        tempList_dux = list(FSoutput_vcf_formatted.loc[i,'duxPredictedGenes'])
        tempList_vcf = list(FSoutput_vcf_formatted.loc[i,'FunseqGeneList'])
        overlap = len(set(tempList_dux) & set(tempList_vcf))
        FSoutput_vcf_formatted.loc[i,'#genesOverlapping'] = overlap

d(FSoutput_vcf_formatted)

print(FSoutput_vcf_formatted['#genesOverlapping'].isna().sum())
# print(FSoutput_vcf_formatted['#genesOverlapping'].value_counts())
FSoutput_vcf_formatted['#genesOverlapping'].hist()

## 1) Calculate Lambda Value, ie the estimate of the slope given by permPvector
pvector<-BRCA_outputDf_promoter$pValue
observedPvector<-sort(pvector,decreasing=F)
permPvector<-1:length(observedPvector)/length(observedPvector)
myLambda <- summary(lm(observedPvector ~ 0 + permPvector))$coeff[1,1]
# PCAWG myLambda = 1.099141.... (if pvector = $qValue column then: 1.409461)
# allSamples myLambda = 1.111153 ($qValue => 1.45778)


pvector<-BRCA_outputDf_enhancer$pValue
observedPvector<-sort(pvector,decreasing=F)
permPvector<-1:length(observedPvector)/length(observedPvector)
myLambda <- summary(lm(observedPvector ~ 0 + permPvector))$coeff[1,1]
# PCAWG myLambda = 1.260714
# allSamples myLambda = 1.083744 ($qValue => 1.372797)

# For the ER+ samples, I went to CCLE and was able to find a file w/ merged mutation calls called "CCLE_mutations.csv" (1,231,281 mutations; from link below) -> 10,743 SNPs in ER+ breast cancer cell lines (21 cell lines) -> lifted over to hg38 -> intersected with peakBed_hg38 -> only 2,153 SNPs in the enhancer regions... I also tried to look at specific cell lines, like MCF7, but they all seem to point back to the CCLE_mutations.csv file (link below)

link to CCLE data: https://depmap.org/portal/download/
link to MCF7 data: https://depmap.org/portal/cell_line/ACH-000019?tab=mutation ; the "Mutation 22Q1 Public" links back to the CCLE_mutations.csv file

3.1 - Formatting Andre's Funseq Files for CNCDriver¶

# ####### On terminal #############

# cd /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/2_FunseqOutput
# cp /home/anf2034/BRCA_*_Funseq_Recurrence_hg19_raw.bed /athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/2_FunseqOutput/andre_BRCA

# python
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

BRCA_EU_hg19 = pd.read_csv('BRCA_EU_Funseq_Recurrence_hg19_raw.bed', sep = r'[\t;]')
BRCA_UK_hg19 = pd.read_csv('BRCA_UK_Funseq_Recurrence_hg19_raw.bed', sep = r'[\t;]')

columns = list(BRCA_UK_hg19.columns) # column names to use when reading in BRCA_US
BRCA_US_hg19 = pd.read_csv('BRCA_US_Funseq_Recurrence_hg19_raw.bed', sep = r'[\t;]', header = None, names = columns)

cohortNames = ['BRCA_EU_hg19', 'BRCA_UK_hg19', 'BRCA_US_hg19']
cohortList = [BRCA_EU_hg19,BRCA_UK_hg19,BRCA_US_hg19]
for n in range(3):
    cohortName = cohortNames[n]
    cohortDf = cohortList[n]
    print(cohortName)
    print(cohortDf.shape)
#     print(cohortDf['cds'].value_counts())
#     hubstring = cohortDf['network.hub']
#     if 'BRCA_REG' in hubstring:
#         print(hubstring)


for cohort in cohortList:
    cohort['MOTIFBR'], cohort['MOTIFG'] = '',''
    for i in cohort.index:
        motifAnalysisString = cohort.loc[i,'motif.analysis']
        if motifAnalysisString.startswith('MOTIFBR'):
            if ('MOTIFG' in motifAnalysisString):
                motifAnalysisList = motifAnalysisString.split(',MOTIFG=')
                MOTIFBR = motifAnalysisList[0][8:] # [0] calls first instance of the list, [8:] takes all the characters after the 
                MOTIFG = motifAnalysisList[1]
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFBR'] = MOTIFBR
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFG'] = MOTIFG
            else:
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFBR'] = motifAnalysisString[8:]
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFG'] = np.nan
        if motifAnalysisString.startswith('MOTIFG'):
            if ('MOTIFBR' in motifAnalysisString):
                motifAnalysisList = motifAnalysisString.split(',MOTIFBR=')
                MOTIFG = motifAnalysisList[0][7:]
                MOTIFBR = motifAnalysisList[1]
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFBR'] = MOTIFBR
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFG'] = MOTIFG
            else:
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFG'] = motifAnalysisString[7:]
                cohort.loc[i,'MOTIFBR'] = np.nan

for n in range(3):
    cohortName = cohortNames[n]
    cohortDf = cohortList[n]
    cohortDf.replace('.', np.NaN, inplace = True)
    cohortDf.to_csv(('/home/acp4001/tempAndreBRCA_'+cohortName+'_formatted.bed'), sep = '\t', header = None, index = None) # next time don't do "header = None", caused more headaches, see below

import pandas as pd
CRISPRiScreen = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/raw_dux_MCF7_RRA_all_guides_slim.txt', sep = '\t')

peakBed_hg19 = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/temp_allPeakBed_hg19.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, names = ['chr_peakBed_hg19', 'start_peakBed_hg19', 'end_peakBed_hg19', 'peak_peakBed_hg19'])
peakBed_hg38 = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/dux2001/EX_0161_fpBRCA/allPeakBed.bed', sep = '\t', names = ['chr_peakBed_hg38', 'start_peakBed_hg38', 'end_peakBed_hg38', 'peak_peakBed_hg38'])
peakBed_hg38.drop(labels = [0], axis = 'index', inplace = True)

CRISPRiScreen = CRISPRiScreen[CRISPRiScreen['Gene'].str.contains('_')] # 15376 -> 14910 rows
CRISPRiScreen.rename(columns = {'Gene': 'peak_CRISPRi'}, inplace = True)

CRISPRiScreen = pd.merge(CRISPRiScreen, peakBed_hg19, how = 'left', left_on = 'peak_CRISPRi', right_on = 'peak_peakBed_hg19')

CRISPRiScreen = pd.merge(CRISPRiScreen, peakBed_hg38, how = 'left', left_on = 'peak_CRISPRi', right_on = 'peak_peakBed_hg38')
# CRISPRiScreen.dropna(subset = ['peak_peakBed'], inplace = True) # 14,910 -> 14,894


CRISPRiScreen['end_peakBed_hg19'] = CRISPRiScreen['end_peakBed_hg19'].astype('Int64') # note: if you just do .astype(int) it throws an error b/c can't convert NaN to int, is rectified if you use "int64"
CRISPRiScreen['start_peakBed_hg19'] = CRISPRiScreen['start_peakBed_hg19'].astype('Int64')
CRISPRiScreen.drop(columns = ['peak_peakBed_hg19', 'peak_peakBed_hg38'], inplace = True)
CRISPRiScreen.sort_values('p_val', inplace = True)
CRISPRiScreen['rank_CRISPRi'] = CRISPRiScreen['p_val'].rank() # rank by p_val instead of p.adj just to actually rank by "most to least" significant, ie 2 rows may have same p.adj but one is slightly more significant by p_val.. did the same for CNCDriver

CRISPRiScreen_sig = CRISPRiScreen[CRISPRiScreen['p.adj'] < 0.05]

peakBed_hg19['start+1_peakBed_hg19'] = peakBed_hg19['start_peakBed_hg19'] + 1 # do this for overlap w/ CNCDriver b/c CNCDriver does posStart+1 to convert from 0-based to 1-based
peakBed_hg19['chr:start-end_peakBed_hg19'] = peakBed_hg19['chr_peakBed_hg19'] + ':' + peakBed_hg19['start+1_peakBed_hg19'].astype(str) + '-' + peakBed_hg19['end_peakBed_hg19'].astype(str)

CNCDriverResults_hg19['enhancerUnitPos'] = CNCDriverResults_hg19['enhancerUnitPos'].str.split(',')
CNCDriverResults_hg19 = CNCDriverResults_hg19.explode('enhancerUnitPos')
CNCDriverResults_hg19 = pd.merge(CNCDriverResults_hg19, peakBed_hg19, how = 'left', left_on = 'enhancerUnitPos', right_on = 'chr:start-end_peakBed_hg19') # 9 out of 1,332 are NaN, ie don't map to any peak, none are particularly high ranking in terms of significance (ie row 674+)
CNCDriverResults_hg19.dropna(subset = ['peak_peakBed_hg19'], inplace = True) # 1332 -> 1323

CNCDriverResults_hg19['chr_CNCDriver'], CNCDriverResults_hg19['start_CNCDriver'], CNCDriverResults_hg19['end_CNCDriver'] = CNCDriverResults_hg19['enhancerUnitPos'].str.split(':|-').str

import pandas as pd
all_CNVs = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/00_raw_files/P5_3.3_EUUKUSmerged_CNVs_hg19.tsv', sep = '\t')
# for actual analysis, drop duplicates of variants (i.e. even if they're in different samples)
temp_allCNVs_forIntersect = all_CNVs[['chromosome','chromosome_start','chromosome_end','variantSampleID']]
temp_allCNVs_forIntersect.to_csv('temp_allCNVs_forIntersect.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)

CRISPRiScreen = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/P5_3.2_formatted_MCF7_RRA_all_guides_slim.txt', sep = '\t') # 14910 rows
CRISPRiScreen_sig = CRISPRiScreen[CRISPRiScreen['p.adj'] < 0.05] # 14910 -> 90
CRISPRiScreen_sig['start_peakBed_hg19'] = CRISPRiScreen_sig['start_peakBed_hg19'].astype(int)
CRISPRiScreen_sig['end_peakBed_hg19'] = CRISPRiScreen_sig['end_peakBed_hg19'].astype(int)
tempdf1 = CRISPRiScreen_sig[['chr_peakBed_hg19','start_peakBed_hg19','end_peakBed_hg19','peak_CRISPRi']]
tempdf1.sort_values(by = ['chr_peakBed_hg19','start_peakBed_hg19','end_peakBed_hg19'], inplace = True)
tempdf1.to_csv('temp_peaks_forIntersect.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)

CRISPRiScreen_insig = CRISPRiScreen[(CRISPRiScreen['p.adj'] > 0.05)] # 14,910 -> 14,820
CRISPRiScreen_insig.dropna(subset = ['p.adj','chr_peakBed_hg19'], inplace = True) # 14,820 -> 14,804; so dropping regions where there was no peakLoc is fine :) only 16 were dropped

CRISPRiScreen_insig['start_peakBed_hg19'] = CRISPRiScreen_insig['start_peakBed_hg19'].astype(int)
CRISPRiScreen_insig['end_peakBed_hg19'] = CRISPRiScreen_insig['end_peakBed_hg19'].astype(int)
tempdf1 = CRISPRiScreen_insig[['chr_peakBed_hg19','start_peakBed_hg19','end_peakBed_hg19','peak_CRISPRi']]
tempdf2 = tempdf1.sample(300)
tempdf2.sort_values(by = ['chr_peakBed_hg19','start_peakBed_hg19','end_peakBed_hg19'], inplace = True)
tempdf2.to_csv('temp_300randomPeaks1_forIntersect.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)

all_gains = all_CNVs[all_CNVs['mutation_type'] == 'gain'][['chromosome','chromosome_start','chromosome_end','variantSampleID']]
all_losses = all_CNVs[all_CNVs['mutation_type'] == 'loss'][['chromosome','chromosome_start','chromosome_end','variantSampleID']]
all_others = all_CNVs[(all_CNVs['mutation_type'] != 'gain') & (all_CNVs['mutation_type'] != 'loss')][['chromosome','chromosome_start','chromosome_end','variantSampleID']]
all_gains.to_csv('temp_allGains_forIntersect.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)
all_losses.to_csv('temp_allLosses_forIntersect.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)
all_others.to_csv('temp_allOthers_forIntersect.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)

# Accounting for the fact that the same region can have 2+ different CNVs in the same sample. i.e.: chr1:1-100_loss_sample1, chr1:20-30_loss_sample1
CRISPRiScreen_sig['donorCounts_allCNVs'] = ''
CRISPRiScreen_sig['donorCounts_allGains'] = ''
CRISPRiScreen_sig['donorCounts_allLosses'] = ''

for i in CRISPRiScreen_sig.index:
    peak = CRISPRiScreen_sig.loc[i,'peak_CRISPRi']
    tempdf = peaksIntersected_allCNVs[peaksIntersected_allCNVs['peak'] == peak]
    CRISPRiScreen_sig.loc[i, 'donorCounts_allCNVs'] = len(tempdf['icgc_donor_ids'].unique())
    tempdf = peaksIntersected_allGains[peaksIntersected_allGains['peak'] == peak]
    CRISPRiScreen_sig.loc[i, 'donorCounts_allGains'] = len(tempdf['icgc_donor_ids'].unique())
    tempdf = peaksIntersected_allLosses[peaksIntersected_allLosses['peak'] == peak]
    CRISPRiScreen_sig.loc[i, 'donorCounts_allLosses'] = len(tempdf['icgc_donor_ids'].unique())

d(CRISPRiScreen_sig,2)
peak_CRISPRi p_val p.adj rank_CRISPRi donorCounts_allCNVs donorCounts_allGains donorCounts_allLosses

438 PCPG_38796 0.012856 0.291127 439.0 0 192 22

python
import pandas as pd
staaf_variants_hg19 = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/1_FunseqInput/staaf/TNBC/raw_TNBC_variantCalls_hg19.bed', sep = '\t')

staaf_variants_hg19['Pos-1'] = staaf_variants_hg19['Pos'] - 1

## Rearrange columns
staaf_variants_hg19.columns # Then use txtformat.com to rearrange as below:
columns = ['Chrom','Pos-1','Pos','Ref','Alt','Sample','#AnalysisProc','Normal','VariantID','Qual','Filter','Gene','Transcript','RNA','CDS','Protein','Type','Effect','DP','MP','GP','TG','TP','SG','SP','DS','SNP','ASRD','CLPM','ASMD','VD','VW','GT-Norm','FAZ-Norm','FCZ-Norm','FGZ-Norm','FTZ-Norm','RAZ-Norm','RCZ-Norm','RGZ-Norm','RTZ-Norm','PM-Norm','GT-Tum','FAZ-Tum','FCZ-Tum','FGZ-Tum','FTZ-Tum','RAZ-Tum','RCZ-Tum','RGZ-Tum','RTZ-Tum','PM-Tum','FLG-DTH','FLG-RP','FLG-MN','FLG-PT','FLG-MQ','FLG-SR','FLG-CR','FLG-PH','FLG-HSD','FLG-GI','FLG-VUM','FLG-SE','FLG-MNP','1000g2015aug_all','ExAC_ALL','avsnp147']

staaf_variants_hg19 = staaf_variants_hg19[columns]

staaf_variants_hg19['Chrom'] = 'chr' + staaf_variants_hg19['Chrom'].astype(str)

staaf_variants_hg19['Sample'] = 'staaf_' + staaf_variants_hg19['Sample']


## code to make sure that the delimiter I use in "temp_allColCombined" is not in any of the columns ---> can't use "_", ';'
# for column in msk_variants.columns:
#     print(msk_variants.loc[0,column])

staaf_variants_hg19['temp_allColCombined'] = staaf_variants_hg19[columns].apply(lambda row: ';'.join(row.values.astype(str)), axis=1)

temp_staaf_variants = staaf_variants_hg19[['Chrom','Pos-1','Pos','temp_allColCombined']]


temp_staaf_variants.to_csv('temp_forLiftOver_staaf.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)

## also save staaf_variants_hg19 in a Funseq Formatted way just in case I want to run Funseq/CNCDriver in hg19 instead :)

python
import pandas as pd
import glob

nikZainal_metadata = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/1_FunseqInput/nikZainal/Supplementary Table 1 CLINICAL.PATHOLOGY.DATA.FREEZE.ANALYSIS.v4.032015.csv', header = [1]) # 560 samples

nikZainal_metadata_TNBC = nikZainal_metadata[(nikZainal_metadata['final.ER'] == 'negative') & (nikZainal_metadata['final.PR'] == 'negative') & (nikZainal_metadata['final.HER2'] == 'negative')] # 163 samples

TNBC_sampleList = nikZainal_metadata_TNBC['sample_name'].unique()
TNBC_sampleList = ['/home/anf2034/BRCA_WGS/BRCA_EU/'+ x + 'a_BRCA_EU_WGS_hg19.bed' for x in TNBC_sampleList] # len = 163

path = r'/home/anf2034/BRCA_WGS/BRCA_EU/' # use your path
all_files = glob.glob(path + "/*.bed") # len 560

temp_TNBC_files = set(TNBC_sampleList) & set(all_files) #len = 154

temp_list = []

for filename in temp_TNBC_files:
    df = pd.read_csv(filename, index_col=None, header=0, names = ['CHROM','START','END','REF','ALT','SAMPLE'], sep = '\t')
    temp_list.append(df)

nikZainal_variants_hg19 = pd.concat(temp_list, ignore_index = True)

columns = nikZainal_variants_hg19.columns

nikZainal_variants_hg19['SAMPLE'] = 'nikZainal_' + nikZainal_variants_hg19['SAMPLE']

temp_nikZainal_variants.to_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/1_FunseqInput/nikZainal/TNBC/temp_forLiftOver_nikZainal.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)

# also save hg19 variants :) 
nikZainal_variants_hg19.drop(columns=['temp_allColCombined'],inplace = True)

    print("Avg Num Muts/sample: ", avgNumMut)

allSamples = pd.concat([PCAWG, staaf, nikZainal, MSK])

PCAWG_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS <- read.csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/2_FunseqOutput/mergedCohorts/TNBC_tnbcTrial1Context_hg19/PCAWG_TNBCtnbcTrial1Context_NCDS.txt', sep = '\t', row.names=NULL, na.strings="")

nikZainal_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS <- read.csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/2_FunseqOutput/mergedCohorts/TNBC_tnbcTrial1Context_hg19/nikZainal_TNBCtnbcTrial1Context_NCDS.txt', sep = '\t', row.names=NULL, na.strings="")
MSK_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS <- read.csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/2_FunseqOutput/mergedCohorts/TNBC_tnbcTrial1Context_hg19/MSK_TNBCtnbcTrial1Context_NCDS.txt', sep = '\t', row.names=NULL, na.strings="")

PCAWG_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS$tumorType <- 'BRCA'
staaf_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS$tumorType <- 'BRCA'
nikZainal_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS$tumorType <- 'BRCA'
MSK_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS$tumorType <- 'BRCA'

df1 <- rbind(PCAWG_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS, staaf_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS)
df2 <- rbind(df1, nikZainal_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS)
reducedFunseqOutputNCDS <- rbind(df2, MSK_reducedFunseqOutputNCDS)

save(reducedFunseqOutputNCDS, file = '/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/2_FunseqOutput/mergedCohorts/TNBC_tnbcTrial1Context_hg19/reducedFunseqOutputNCDS_BRCA.Rd', version = 3.6)

python
df = pd.read_csv('raw_Fredriksson_et_al_2014_BRCA_mutation.txt', sep = '\t')
df['pos-1'] = df['pos'] - 1
df['chr'] = 'chr' + df['chr'].astype(str)
tempdf = df[['chr','pos-1','pos','ref_allele','var_allele','barcode']]

tempdf = tempdf[(~tempdf['var_allele'].str.startswith('-')) & (~tempdf['var_allele'].str.startswith('+'))]
tempdf.to_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/1_FunseqInput/CTCFppr/BRCA/BRCA_variantCalls_FunseqFormatted_hg19.bed', header = None, index = None, sep = '\t')

tempdf = df[['chr','pos-1','pos','ref_allele','var_allele','barcode','var_freq','varscan_p', 'cancer']]

columns = tempdf.columns
tempdf['temp_allColCombined'] = tempdf[columns].apply(lambda row: ';'.join(row.values.astype(str)), axis=1)
tempdf = tempdf[['chr','pos-1','pos','temp_allColCombined']]
tempdf.to_csv('temp_forLiftOver_CTCFppr.bed', sep = '\t', header = None, index = None)

7.0 - CNCDriver Output, Preliminary Analysis¶

  • KEY
    • 1) Ac = All cancers, Bo = Brca only, To = TNBC only
    • 2) Ae = All elements, Po = Promoter only, Eo = Enhancer only
    • 3) Av = All variants (ie completeData for ourSamples), Co = Candidates only (ie candidate variants in PCAWGppr or BRCA_outputDf/DBScan clusters in ourSamples), So = Significant only

PCAWGppr_AcAeCo_geneList = PCAWGppr_AcAeCo['gene']
allOurs_ToAeCo_geneList = []
allOurs_ToAeSo_geneList = []
for key in cohortdic_ToPoCo:
#     print(key)
    df = cohortdic_ToPoCo[key]
    allOurs_ToAeCo_geneList.extend(df['elementPos'])
    df1 = df[df['qValue'] < 0.1]
    allOurs_ToAeSo_geneList.extend(df1['elementPos'])
for key in cohortdic_ToEoCo:
    df = cohortdic_ToEoCo[key]
    allOurs_ToAeCo_geneList.extend(df['elementPos'])
    df1 = df[df['qValue'] < 0.1]
    allOurs_ToAeSo_geneList.extend(df1['elementPos'])

########################################    
## allOurGenes  allPCAWG genes
PCAWGppr_allOurs_AcAeCo_overlappedGenes = overlap(allOurs_ToAeCo_geneList, PCAWGppr_AcAeCo_geneList, Print = True, Make = True)

## add superEnh positions to "Enhancer-Gene Pairs" in funseq2 (the TNBC_sample_drm.gene_hg19.bed)
superEnh = pd.read_excel('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/P5_AOCproject/dataFromLit/raw_Huang_superEnhToGene_41467_2021_22445_MOESM4_ESM.xlsx', header = [1])
duxPeaks = pd.read_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg19_data_context/TNBC_sample_drm.gene_hg19.bed', sep = '\t', header = None) # these are just the peaks w/ links present in 1+ TNBC sample

temp_superEnh = superEnh[['SE chromosome', 'SE start', 'SE end','gene name']]
temp_superEnh.columns = [0,1,2,3]
temp_duxPeaks = duxPeaks[[0,1,2,3]]

TNBC_withSuperEnh_drm = pd.concat([temp_duxPeaks,temp_superEnh]) # 44471 -> 44802 rows

TNBC_withSuperEnh_drm.to_csv('/athena/khuranalab/scratch/acp4001/funseq_hg19_data_context/TNBC_withSuperEnh_drm.gene_hg19.bed', sep = '\t', header = False, index = False)

observedPvector<-sort(pvector,decreasing=F)
permPvector<-1:length(observedPvector)/length(observedPvector)
myLambda <- summary(lm(observedPvector ~ 0 + permPvector))$coeff[1,1]
